Analyzing the Star Lifecycle using the Hertzsprung Russell Diagram

Abby Stokes

2024-11-24



Introduction

There are many different types of stars, including dwarfs, main sequence (like our sun) and giants, each of which represent a star at a different stage in its lifecycle. Stars with low starting mass are more likely to develop into dwarf stars, whereas highly massive stars are more likely to evolve into a super or hyper giant.



HR Diagram

The Hertzprung-Russell diagram shows the relationship between star absolute magnitude and temperature.



Dataset

The Star Dataset used for this analysis comes from Kaggle, and includes information on 240 different stars, evenly distributed across 6 different star types (40 each). Star types are as follows:

  • Brown Dwarf
  • Red Dwarf
  • White Dwarf
  • Main Sequence
  • Supergiant
  • Hypergiant


Dataset

Each observation contains 7 star attributes including

  • Absolute Temperature (in K)
  • Relative Luminosity (L/Lo)
  • Relative Radius (R/Ro)
  • Absolute Magnitude (Mv)
  • Star Color
  • Spectral Class (O,B,A,F,G,K,M)
  • Star Type (Red Dwarf, Brown Dwarf, White Dwarf, Main Sequence , SuperGiants, HyperGiants)

Conclusions and Future Work

Future Work:

  • Build a classification model to predict star type based on attributes such as color, temperature, absolute magnitude, etc.

Conclusion:

  • Our dataset very closely followed the patterns as expected by the HR diagram and star life cycle theory.
  • HR diagram is a very effective way to portray many different aspects of a given star in just one chart!
